name: @kampoengbatoe2699
comment: India is a developed country, and by 2024 will take over the US as the world number 1 superpower. The whole country (literally all cities, towns and villages) are vastly clean, modern and futuristic, with zero crime rate and absolutely zero pollution. Its capital New Delhi is well known as the cleanest city on earth. There are no slumps, shit-holes, ghettos or poor uneducated hungry people in any corner of India. Each and every Indian is dead honest - no need to worry if you drop wallet on the street, they will always return it to you untouched. India is totally free of beggars, thieves, scammers, thugs, mafia and gangsters. Its government is very clean, corruption-free and has consistently achieved zero unemployment for decades. Public transportation and infrastructure is always no.1 in the world. Public safety is way better than even country like Japan - very very safe for women to walk alone at night anywhere in India. Indian police force is remarkably professional, corruption-free and humane - they don't take bribes, they don't extort money, they don't protect scammers or organized crime, they don't rape male and female inmates inside prison cells, or beat ordinary citizens on the streets brutally with batons or long rods (like what you usually see on youtube). And at least half of Indian population (about 700 millions) are totally committed to support climate change by having a strong habit of pooing everywhere anywhere in open space everyday (not in toilets, there is no toilet anyway) to fertilize soil naturally and save water (no need to flush anyway, right?). Such amazing and fantastic achievements by Modi and his BJP in making India the world most developed country. Bravo Bravo Bravo.

name: @solaraspect5255
comment: India will become a larger economy over time, that's simply time+large population+investments=faster economic activity. But will it have exponential growth from 2030-2070? Probably not. Goldmans Sachs are working with incomplete data, and the future is impossible to predict. So will India have higher quality goods and more exports? Yes, but to which degree depends largely on the political leadership and the cultural willingness to adapt to new modes of living.   As a side note, I would just like to add that this video uses outdated and selective data for digital adoption and manufactured goods. I'm sure the video creator has a good reason for doing this in telling his story, but you can easily find a more complete picture yourself if you look up Digital Adoption Index or Industrial Production Index (a many more datasets that go deeper from macro to microeconomics). And just as young demographics can be both a blessing and a curse depending on the education and healthcare capabilities of the country, so too can specialization and diversification both lead to boom-bust cycles and stagnation. Specialization in a handful of sectors can be a viable strategy, to a certain extent, just not only in one or two so that a market crash destroys the national economy (see Greece with tourism+shipping or Iceland with financial services).
